  "What is 'reduced row echelon form' (RREF)?": "",
  "Any upper triangular matrix, particularly regarding only according to conventional analysis": "",
  "A form where each pivot is 1 and is the only nonzero entry in its column, with pivots stepping right and zero rows at the bottom": "",
  "A form where all entries below each pivot are zero based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "A matrix whose diagonal entries are all equal when evaluated systematically": "",
  "RREF requires: (1) each leading entry (pivot) is 1, (2) each pivot is the only nonzero entry in its column, (3) pivots move to the right as you go down rows, and (4) all-zero rows are at the bottom.": "",
  "What does 'back elimination' (or 'upward elimination') mean in Gauss-Jordan elimination?": "",
  "Eliminating entries below each pivot": "",
  "Reversing all row operations": "",
  "Solving for variables starting from the first equation": "",
  "Eliminating entries above each pivot so that each pivot column contains only the pivot 1": "",
  "Back elimination (or upward elimination) is the second phase of Gauss-Jordan elimination where entries above each pivot are zeroed out, working from the bottom-right pivot upward.": "",
  "What does it mean for the RREF of a matrix to be unique?": "",
  "Every matrix has exactly one RREF, regardless of which sequence of row operations is used": "",
  "Only square matrices have a unique RREF": "",
  "The RREF is unique only when the determinant is nonzero": "",
  "Every matrix can only be reduced by one specific sequence of row operations": "",
  "A fundamental theorem states that every matrix has a unique RREF. While the sequence of row operations may differ, the final RREF is always the same.": "",
  "What does 'scaling a row' mean in Gauss-Jordan elimination?": "",
  "Moving a row to a different position": "",
  "Multiplying every entry in a row by the same nonzero constant": "",
  "Deleting a row from the matrix": "",
  "Adding a row to itself": "",
  "Scaling a row means multiplying all entries in that row by a nonzero scalar. This is used to make pivot entries equal to 1 in Gauss-Jordan elimination.": "",
  "What is a 'basic variable' in the context of RREF?": "",
  "A variable whose corresponding column contains a pivot": "",
  "A variable that can take any value": "",
  "A variable from the first equation only": "",
  "A variable that equals zero": "",
  "A basic variable corresponds to a pivot column in the RREF. Its value is determined by the system (expressed in terms of free variables and constants).": "",
  "What does 'parametric form' mean when describing solutions after Gauss-Jordan elimination?": "",
  "Using determinants to express each variable": "",
  "Listing all possible numerical solutions": "",
  "Writing the solution as a single number": "",
  "Expressing basic variables in terms of free variables, which serve as parameters": "",
  "When a system has free variables, the parametric form expresses each basic variable as a function of the free variables (parameters), describing the entire family of solutions.": "",
  "What is the 'rank' of a matrix as revealed by its RREF?": "",
  "The total number of entries in the matrix": "",
  "The determinant of the matrix": "",
  "The number of columns in the matrix": "",
  "The number of nonzero rows (equivalently, the number of pivots) in the RREF": "",
  "The rank of a matrix equals the number of pivot positions in its RREF, which is the same as the number of nonzero rows after reduction.": "",
  "What does it mean for a system to be 'overdetermined'?": "",
  "The system has the same number of equations and unknowns": "",
  "The system has more equations than unknowns": "",
  "The system has no free variables": "",
  "The system has more unknowns than equations": "",
  "An overdetermined system has more equations than unknowns. It may still be consistent if the extra equations are compatible, but often such systems have no exact solution.": "",
  "What does 'underdetermined system' mean?": "",
  "A system whose coefficient matrix is square": "",
  "A system that has no solution": "",
  "A system that can only be solved by computers": "",
  "A system with fewer equations than unknowns, typically leading to free variables": "",
  "An underdetermined system has fewer equations than unknowns. If consistent, it has infinitely many solutions because there are more unknowns than constraints.": "",
  "What does it mean for a pivot to be the 'only nonzero entry in its column' in RREF?": "",
  "The column contains no entries at all except the pivot": "",
  "The pivot entry is larger than all other entries in the column": "",
  "The pivot column has a 1 in the pivot row and 0 in every other row": "",
  "All columns must have exactly one nonzero entry": "",
  "In RREF, each pivot column looks like a column of the identity matrix: a single 1 in the pivot position and 0 in all other rows. This is what distinguishes RREF from ordinary row echelon form.": "",
